Tell me about yourself:
- I completed Masters Degree in Network Engineering from University of Colorado Boulder

- I joined Visa as a Network Engineer in the Operations team as a Network Engineer
    - My main focus area was Datacenter Networking, initially with the traditional 3 tier architecture setup using Cisco Nexus Core switches, Cisco L2 switches, Palo Alto Firewalls and F5 loadbalancers to partition the network into multiple security zones and loadbalance the requests.
    - My day to day involved T-shooting issues related to HSRP, OSPF, BGP neighborships, traffic shifts using OSPF/BGP Metrics.
    - For client connectivity issues, lead Sev1/2 Calls and perform path trace route to check for sub-optimal routing, interface errors, discards, take packet captures and utilize wireshark to deep dive into packets, perform tcp analysis (check for re-transmissions, check for RST flag from client)
    - Documenting post impact analysis using tools like solarwinds, splunk (To look for OSPF/BGP Flaps during the time of the event), check Thousand Eyes to confirm if there was 
      a big event some where on the internet

- Meanwhile, I got promoted to Staff Network Engineer
    - Mentor Junior members of the team to cover weekend Shifts for oncall, knowledge transfer and drive changes through them
    - Got involved with Engineering teams in the Migration project to CLOS VXLAN fabric for green field deployments using Arista/Cumulus switches
    - Created operational runbooks containing SOP for the operations team. Set up alarming and do failover (alert) testing before making the network operational 
    - Because, we were using static flooding initially, lot of times we had to configure the vlan/vni mapping manually, later we move to evpn using mBGP
    - We also onboarded CDN services from Akamai/Cloudflare for Web traffic (which acted like a Global traffic manager) and advertised anycast address for which
      we had to make changes to the Web FW to allow list the IP ranges
    - Take lead on the Sev1/2 Calls, t-shot issues and followed up later to improve the network, used API calls to various backends to create metric reports to prove our case 
    - I took few automation initiatives in the team:
        - Using SNMP traps, trigger condition to > 3 ospf flaps to raise ospf tunnel cost via netmiko
        - Using Jinja templating, create scripts and changes that would take hours to do manually before to do circuit upgrades
        - Create API calls to get top talkers from packet capture probes and report it for different traffic flows
        - Derive the server name from switch mac address table and send a notification to the owners of a maintanance window

- I moved to AWS as a NDE II 
    - I started design/planning datacenter interconnectivity networks using topology planning tool called Cariden.
    - The scaling plans were created for coming 2 Years using the demand data for organic (15% year over year) and inorganic (rack landings) traffic
    - Constraints used to design were Fiber constraints, Building constraints (Rack Space Power Cooling) , 75% traffic threshold and failure SLAs like Fiber Cuts, Building failure, traffic failure and traffic profiles (North <> South vs East <> West) and datacenter redundancy for an availability zone
    - Design Reviews from other engineers, provide feedback, mentor engineers for automating tasks, delegate work and get projects delivered through others
    - Collaborated with Principle Engineers, review designs by other engineers and suggested improvements here
    - Moved to Datacenter Automation and Deployment team, Created Python Packages for End-End workflows of Fabric deployments, created common python classes and functions
      that could be used across the teams. 
    - Made YAML file changes, reviewed code changes by other members, performed unit test, lab testing, and integ testing of the product.
    - Create HLD Design for a product, create sprint tasks and mentored junior members to delegate and get work done.
    - Led cross functional goals with Firewall team to automate their process to improve land to live times for new datacenters. (Example: Create reserving mechanism)
    - Tshot switch build, link testing issues with onsite delivery teams as part of oncall rotation.

To summarize, I have overall experience in operating, designing and automating datacenter networks. I enjoy collaborating, working through others, mentoring and getting
impactful results
