Toughest problem you solved, most challenging situation, biggest network problem? Describe something you built and are proud off?
Tell me about your most successful project or Tell me about a time when you were handling a project that went outside of your scope of work. How did you handle it?
Describe a situation where you had to deal with ambiguity when making a decision?
Tell me about a time when you were faced with a problem that had a number of possible solutions. What was the problem and how did you determine the course of action? What was the outcome of that choice? Or When did you take a risk, make a mistake, or fail? How did you respond, and how did you grow from that experience?

S I was the regional owner for designing APAC regions, specifically China region.
T The scaling plans were suppose to be created for coming 2 Years using the demand data for organic (15% year over year) and inorganic (rack landings) traffic
  Constraints used to design were Fiber constraints, Building constraints (Rack Space Power Cooling) , 75% traffic threshold and failure SLAs like Fiber Cuts, Building failure,
  traffic failure and traffic profiles (North <> South vs East <> West) and datacenter redundancy for an availability zone
A While designing the network I came across 2 challenges,
  1. The traffic demands were absurdly high (generally we would rely on intake from the telemetry team which consisted of principle engineers), they had no networking knowledge
     so they did not consider the power constraints and space constraints in some of the datacenters while accounting for rack landings which threw off their calculations. Also they had 
     considered a organic growth of 50% based on past year growth but the region had matured to warrant only 15% growth. After collaborating with the team and getting the correct 
     data I started planning the network.
  2. I planned the network as per the demands and constraints, but later at the final moment when my design was about to be approved and orders were suppose to be placed there was
     another issue. In China the fiber delivery is controlled by China Telecom and they denied providing more dark fiber for AWS as they were not getting enough business from us,
     to upgrade circuits between 2 DCs. So, I had to re-design the network and made proposals to avoid scaling on that path which had to be re-approved.
R Due to the time constraints, I was under pressure to lock in the design by the deadline which I was suppose to do which was praised by the Principal NEs as well.

S I was in the Operations team at Visa, there came a Sev1 call to troubleshoot an issue where an application url was broken
T Task was to perform troubleshooting, the application IP was suppose to be a Front VIP on a F5 loadbalancer facing the internet. There were 2 F5 Loadbalancers in Active/Passive 
  Setup. I Checked the Active F5 Device and saw that the config for the URL was missing. I checked  with the application team on the call and understood that the VIP was configured 
  a day before and was working till 30 minutes back. 
A I checked the logs and saw that there was a manual sync performed from the standby F5 to active F5. I checked the standby and saw that the VIP was missing there as well but
  confirmed that the change was indeed performed yesterday so started to think and create a theory. Before that, created the VIP on the Active LB again and the service started to 
  work
R After diving deep, understood that the vip was created on active and the change was not synced (The changes are sync via a cron job every 24 hours automatically)
  30 minutes back some engineer changed a vip on the passive LB and synced to active which deleted the vip that was created yesterday causing issues. Took multiple AIs like
  Only perform change on Active and always perform sync after that, never sync from passive to active
